# YourDomi â€” Cursor AI Rules
# Based on everything-claude-code best practices, adapted for React/Vite/TypeScript

## Project Context
This is YourDomi (yourdomi.be), a Belgian short-term rental property management platform.
Stack: React, Vite, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, deployed on Vercel.
The app includes: property analysis tools, deal scoring, owner earnings projections,
permit/compliance guides (Praktische Gids), and lead capture flows.

---

## Core Principles

### 1. Plan Before You Code
- For any feature touching more than 2 files, outline the approach before writing code
- Identify side effects, shared state changes, and component dependencies first
- Ask clarifying questions before making assumptions on business logic

### 2. Immutability (CRITICAL)
- Always create new objects/arrays â€” never mutate existing ones
- Use spread operators, map, filter, reduce â€” never push/splice/direct assignment
- React state must always be set via setState with new references, never mutated in place

### 3. Component Architecture
- Prefer many small, focused components over large monolithic ones
- Max ~150 lines per component file; extract sub-components if exceeding this
- Co-locate related files: Component.tsx, Component.types.ts, Component.test.tsx
- Keep business logic out of components â€” extract to custom hooks or utility functions

### 4. TypeScript
- Always define explicit types for props, API responses, and state shapes
- Never use `any` â€” use `unknown` and narrow with type guards if type is uncertain
- Define shared types in a central `types/` directory
- Use discriminated unions for complex state (e.g. loading/error/success states)

### 5. Security
- NEVER hardcode API keys, tokens, or secrets in source code
- All secrets go in `.env` files â€” reference via `import.meta.env.VITE_*`
- Validate and sanitize all user inputs before processing
- Never expose internal data structures or error details to the UI

### 6. Naming & Style
- Components: PascalCase (e.g. `PropertyCard`, `DealScoreWidget`)
- Hooks: camelCase with `use` prefix (e.g. `usePropertyAnalysis`)
- Utils/helpers: camelCase (e.g. `calculateOwnerEarnings`)
- Constants: SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE (e.g. `MAX_DEAL_SCORE`)
- Files: match the primary export name (e.g. `PropertyCard.tsx` for `PropertyCard`)

### 7. Styling (Tailwind)
- Use Tailwind utility classes; avoid inline styles except for truly dynamic values
- Define brand colors and spacing in `tailwind.config.ts` â€” don't hardcode hex values
- Use `cn()` utility (clsx/tailwind-merge) for conditional class names
- Keep responsive variants consistent: mobile-first with `md:` and `lg:` breakpoints

### 8. Data Fetching & State
- Use React Query (or similar) for server state â€” don't store API data in useState
- Separate server state (API data) from UI state (modals, form inputs)
- Always handle loading, error, and empty states explicitly â€” never leave them implicit
- Debounce expensive calculations and API calls triggered by user input

### 9. Performance
- Memoize expensive computations with `useMemo`
- Memoize stable callback references with `useCallback` when passing to child components
- Lazy-load routes and heavy components with `React.lazy` + `Suspense`
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders: check component dependencies before adding to state

### 10. Git & Commits
- Commit format: `<type>: <description>`
  - Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `style`, `test`, `chore`
  - Example: `feat: add deal score visualization to property report`
- Keep commits atomic â€” one logical change per commit
- Never commit `.env` files or any file containing secrets

---

## YourDomi-Specific Patterns

### Property Analysis Reports
- Deal scores are always between 0â€“100; display with color coding (red/amber/green)
- Owner earnings projections must show monthly and annual breakdowns
- Permit/compliance content is city-specific â€” always check `city` prop before rendering

### Lead Capture
- Lead modal must always have a visible close mechanism
- Form validation runs on submit, not on every keystroke
- On successful submission, show confirmation before redirecting

### Calculations
- All currency is EUR â€” format with `Intl.NumberFormat('nl-BE', { style: 'currency', currency: 'EUR' })`
- Occupancy rates are expressed as decimals (0.72) internally, percentages (72%) in UI
- Never display raw API numbers directly â€” always run through formatter functions

---

## What NOT To Do
- Don't use `console.log` in committed code â€” use a proper logger or remove before commit
- Don't add dependencies without checking bundle size impact first
- Don't create files over 300 lines â€” split them
- Don't use `// @ts-ignore` â€” fix the type issue properly
- Don't leave TODO comments in committed code without a linked issue
- Don't fetch data directly in components â€” use hooks or query functions
